[SPEAKER_01]: So we have a number of a pool of individuals who fit that.

542
00:48:30,511 --> 00:48:38,955
[SPEAKER_01]: Insofar as the other open position, the 60-40, we're holding that open at the moment.

543
00:48:39,672 --> 00:48:44,593
[SPEAKER_00]: Yeah, we didn't fund it because we needed an extra lead.

544
00:48:45,474 --> 00:48:45,734
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes.

545
00:48:47,434 --> 00:48:48,974
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, we have an extra lead.

546
00:48:49,034 --> 00:48:58,837
[SPEAKER_01]: We had an open lead mechanic and Stephen Burkholzer is going to be promoted to a lead mechanic.

547
00:48:59,577 --> 00:49:07,479
[SPEAKER_01]: And Teresa, I know I had discussions with Steve relative to Christopher Makara.

548
00:49:08,479 --> 00:49:16,923
[SPEAKER_01]: also becoming a lead, but he is listed here as a labor mechanic.

549
00:49:17,103 --> 00:49:25,907
[SPEAKER_01]: So that both of those individuals at Steve's recommendation were going to be promoted based upon the approval of the budget.

550
00:49:26,067 --> 00:49:31,570
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'm going to recommend that we come back with a

551
00:49:34,732 --> 00:49:42,977
[SPEAKER_01]: to amend this at some point in time, but with the full knowledge that both of those individuals, based on Steve's recommendation, would be lead mechanics.

552
00:49:43,778 --> 00:49:56,306
[SPEAKER_01]: And what happened there was that the 160-40 will be eliminated and Christopher will go to the, that's what it is, that's why it's open now that I think of it, Paul.

553
00:49:57,667 --> 00:50:01,169
[SPEAKER_01]: Chris will become a lead mechanic, the increase will be

554
00:50:03,255 --> 00:50:10,326
[SPEAKER_01]: relatively small, it'll be about $2 an hour, and that will be eliminating his position.

555
00:50:11,918 --> 00:50:18,180
[SPEAKER_00]: We're going to trade one of our 6040s for a lead mechanic, and it costs us about $6,000 to do that.

556
00:50:18,240 --> 00:50:21,261
[SPEAKER_00]: So that's what we're going to do.

557
00:50:21,881 --> 00:50:37,006
[SPEAKER_01]: And again, with the same philosophy going forward is that we felt, both maintenance and myself, we felt that these were two individuals who do an excellent job and we didn't want to, we don't want to end up losing them.

558
00:50:40,446 --> 00:50:45,330
[SPEAKER_01]: We don't get, we don't have any issues with the union because of their seniority.

559
00:50:46,611 --> 00:50:48,612
[SPEAKER_01]: And we took that into consideration also.

560
00:50:50,434 --> 00:50:51,514
[SPEAKER_04]: Madam Chairman, if I may.

561
00:50:53,796 --> 00:50:55,778
[SPEAKER_04]: Plummer's position is open.

562
00:50:57,419 --> 00:51:00,701
[SPEAKER_04]: Two painting positions vacant.

563
00:51:02,583 --> 00:51:07,747
[SPEAKER_04]: And you've lost a lot of people in the last three or four years, is that right?

564
00:51:12,472 --> 00:51:19,118
[SPEAKER_01]: I think comparatively speaking, Michael, as far as the number of employees we have, we've not lost a good number.

565
00:51:19,699 --> 00:51:20,980
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know what the percentage is.

566
00:51:21,841 --> 00:51:24,463
[SPEAKER_04]: You haven't had much of a turnover in the office?

567
00:51:26,746 --> 00:51:32,752
[SPEAKER_01]: We have had turnover in certain positions, but overall, I think the

568
00:51:34,743 --> 00:51:38,965
[SPEAKER_01]: I think the staff has been somewhat constant, but there has been turnover, no question about it.

569
00:51:38,985 --> 00:51:43,808
[SPEAKER_01]: The pandemic has hurt us, but we've had a number of folks who've retired.

570
00:51:46,029 --> 00:51:47,310
[SPEAKER_01]: That has occurred.

571
00:51:48,190 --> 00:51:52,973
[SPEAKER_01]: You mentioned the plumber, that position we've been trying to fill.

572
00:51:52,993 --> 00:51:57,135
[SPEAKER_01]: I have an interview tomorrow, now that we can, as the board voted,

573
00:51:58,213 --> 00:52:01,677
[SPEAKER_01]: and approved the new contract, which said now we can look at journeymen, not just masters.

574
00:52:01,937 --> 00:52:04,260
[SPEAKER_01]: And I know I've spoken to some of the commissioners here about that.

575
00:52:05,541 --> 00:52:06,742
[SPEAKER_01]: Like I said, I have an interview tomorrow.

576
00:52:06,762 --> 00:52:09,565
[SPEAKER_01]: It's the first interview I have in a plumber's position in almost two years.

577
00:52:10,266 --> 00:52:12,329
[SPEAKER_01]: Michael left almost three years ago.

578
00:52:12,349 --> 00:52:13,530
[SPEAKER_01]: It'll be three years in January.

579
00:52:14,151 --> 00:52:15,112
[SPEAKER_01]: We haven't been able to fill that.

580
00:52:15,452 --> 00:52:18,656
[SPEAKER_01]: The painting positions that are budgeted there, that are open,

581
00:52:19,476 --> 00:52:27,341
[SPEAKER_01]: We've not filled those since one of our maintenance, excuse me, since our painter left four years ago.

582
00:52:27,921 --> 00:52:28,782
[SPEAKER_01]: We've kept those open.

583
00:52:29,182 --> 00:52:36,486
[SPEAKER_01]: And we've kept them open because we would have to negotiate with the union to take them off.

584
00:52:36,666 --> 00:52:41,449
[SPEAKER_01]: So we keep them in, but we have the opportunity not to fill those if we so desire.

585
00:52:42,727 --> 00:52:43,267
[SPEAKER_08]: Placeholders.

586
00:52:44,508 --> 00:52:48,809
[SPEAKER_01]: It's the same thing with Steve Burkholz's promotion.

587
00:52:49,649 --> 00:52:53,330
[SPEAKER_01]: He is going to a lead mechanic position that's been vacant since I've been here.

588
00:52:54,630 --> 00:52:56,891
[SPEAKER_01]: It's been open, I'll put it that way, not vacant, open.

589
00:52:57,511 --> 00:52:59,812
[SPEAKER_08]: Once you take a position out, it's really hard to put it back on.

590
00:53:00,112 --> 00:53:01,412
[SPEAKER_01]: Exactly, exactly.

591
00:53:01,952 --> 00:53:03,973
[SPEAKER_01]: So it doesn't mean that we need to fill it.

592
00:53:04,113 --> 00:53:05,953
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, it's not funded right, exactly.

593
00:53:06,053 --> 00:53:11,515
[SPEAKER_00]: And I think we've determined that, to a certain extent, painting, that the contracting has been

594
00:53:11,873 --> 00:53:13,654
[SPEAKER_01]: Well, the contract has been doing it.

595
00:53:13,674 --> 00:53:14,575
[SPEAKER_00]: We were able to get painters.

596
00:53:14,595 --> 00:53:19,779
[SPEAKER_01]: But also in the last contract, the issue there was that the maintenance staff did not want to do painting.

597
00:53:20,680 --> 00:53:28,005
[SPEAKER_01]: And in the last contract, we negotiated that they would get a dollar and a half more per hour for every hour that they painted.

598
00:53:28,686 --> 00:53:32,709
[SPEAKER_01]: And they do a minimal amount of painting, but what it was previously was they'd only do 24 inches.

599
00:53:33,589 --> 00:53:36,511
[SPEAKER_01]: If they had to patch something, they'd only paint 24 inches.

600
00:53:36,531 --> 00:53:37,512
[SPEAKER_01]: That's what they did before.

601
00:53:37,872 --> 00:53:40,715
[SPEAKER_01]: Now they'll paint the whole wall.

602
00:53:43,553 --> 00:53:55,063
[SPEAKER_01]: So we've made some great strides in that, and as I mentioned to the board previously, when we talked about the union contract, this year's negotiations were the best that I've seen in the last 10 years.

603
00:53:55,903 --> 00:54:00,067
[SPEAKER_01]: In the last 10 years, even to the extent, as I indicated to the board, that they were willing to tack on another year.

604
00:54:01,307 --> 00:54:03,809
[SPEAKER_01]: so that we're not just a year out, we're two years out.

605
00:54:04,249 --> 00:54:07,631
[SPEAKER_01]: But Michael, no, in answer to your question, yeah, we have had some turnover.

606
00:54:07,671 --> 00:54:28,163
[SPEAKER_01]: Last year, I should say this year, during the winter, we had, and it's extraordinary that we were able to get through with it, but we had an occasion where all four of our leased housing coordinators left, left, and they left in large part because of their own health.

607
00:54:29,691 --> 00:54:35,336
[SPEAKER_01]: and they left with having nothing to do with the authority, unfortunately.

608
00:54:35,356 --> 00:54:53,732
[SPEAKER_01]: And we ended up being able to, with the assistance of Jennifer and our Director of Management and the Lease Housing Director, Samara, along with bringing in folks from other housing authorities who worked with us at night at times, we still have

609
00:54:54,797 --> 00:54:58,880
[SPEAKER_01]: Kathy Melpus, who is a previous employee.

610
00:54:58,960 --> 00:55:00,461
[SPEAKER_01]: She came back and helped us out.

611
00:55:01,001 --> 00:55:09,506
[SPEAKER_01]: Linda DiProfio, who used to be the director of leased housing in Somerville, comes in a couple of days a week to assist, even to this point.

612
00:55:10,646 --> 00:55:13,988
[SPEAKER_01]: So the pandemic has been very tough.

613
00:55:14,048 --> 00:55:15,669
[SPEAKER_01]: It's all hands on deck, to be quite frank.

614
00:55:15,709 --> 00:55:22,473
[SPEAKER_01]: And as I said earlier, you come in here at nighttime at six o'clock, seven o'clock,

615
00:55:23,104 --> 00:55:24,465
[SPEAKER_01]: I left at 9.30 the other day.

616
00:55:25,005 --> 00:55:26,305
[SPEAKER_01]: Barbara left early the other night.

617
00:55:26,425 --> 00:55:27,205
[SPEAKER_01]: She left at 7.00.

618
00:55:28,926 --> 00:55:30,446
[SPEAKER_01]: And when she left, there was still staff here.

619
00:55:30,847 --> 00:55:31,687
[SPEAKER_01]: There was still staff.

620
00:55:31,747 --> 00:55:39,469
[SPEAKER_01]: So, you know, I would love not to have to do that, but, you know, we end up having to, like I said, it's all hands on deck.

621
00:55:40,150 --> 00:55:44,411
[SPEAKER_01]: And as Theresa indicated, you know, Michael, what time do you get here in the morning, Michael?

622
00:55:44,431 --> 00:55:44,411
5.30?

623
00:55:44,451 --> 00:55:45,271
[SPEAKER_01]: 6.30.

624
00:55:44,771 --> 00:55:45,271
[SPEAKER_01]: 6.30 in the morning.

625
00:55:48,136 --> 00:55:52,161
[SPEAKER_01]: 6.30 in the morning, so it's really a dedicated staff.

626
00:55:52,622 --> 00:55:53,964
[SPEAKER_00]: It's better traffic from Bridger.

627
00:55:53,984 --> 00:55:56,548
[SPEAKER_00]: He could have said 5.30, we wouldn't have checked up on him.

628
00:55:56,668 --> 00:55:57,870
[SPEAKER_03]: He would have been here tomorrow morning.

629
00:56:02,938 --> 00:56:03,939
[SPEAKER_01]: He leaves at 5.30.

630
00:56:05,761 --> 00:56:17,833
[SPEAKER_01]: I have to echo what Teresa is saying is the fact that they do an excellent job of making sure that everything is down to the penny.

631
00:56:18,653 --> 00:56:29,240
[SPEAKER_01]: And what I like to see is that HUD looks at what it is that we submit, knowing full well that these two folks are very experienced.

632
00:56:29,661 --> 00:56:35,524
[SPEAKER_01]: And in Michael's instance, also the same as Teresa, but in Michael's instance, they know him not only from here, but they know him from another authority.

633
00:56:38,486 --> 00:56:43,510
[SPEAKER_01]: They're thought of very highly and we're fortunate to have both of them on our team.

634
00:56:44,211 --> 00:56:48,974
[SPEAKER_01]: And you've heard me say this before, we've got a very strong team and we took a hit.

635
00:56:56,326 --> 00:56:58,107
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's going to take something.

636
00:56:58,127 --> 00:57:00,188
[SPEAKER_01]: You can see my voice breaks.

637
00:57:01,048 --> 00:57:03,870
[SPEAKER_01]: It's going to take something for us to get over that.

638
00:57:03,950 --> 00:57:04,390
[SPEAKER_01]: We will.

639
00:57:05,430 --> 00:57:07,812
[SPEAKER_01]: John is here first thing in the morning.

640
00:57:07,872 --> 00:57:12,014
[SPEAKER_01]: When I say first thing in the morning, he's probably driving in at the same time Michael is, if not earlier.

641
00:57:12,694 --> 00:57:17,417
[SPEAKER_01]: I came in at 6.30 on Monday, and the place was entirely unlocked.

642
00:57:17,457 --> 00:57:18,197
[SPEAKER_01]: All the lights were on.

643
00:57:20,282 --> 00:57:25,728
[SPEAKER_01]: John had already been here by that time, but we'll get the job done.

644
00:57:26,189 --> 00:57:33,998
[SPEAKER_01]: And where we're going right now, I wish, and I meant to do this if I can pull it up on here before we leave.

645
00:57:34,939 --> 00:57:38,263
[SPEAKER_01]: I will read to you at least one of the comments I got.

646
00:57:39,178 --> 00:57:55,507
[SPEAKER_01]: from the architect who was designing this building and the compliments that he paid to Steve just to, you know, was right on about what a valuable asset he was to them when they were designing this.

647
00:57:55,927 --> 00:58:04,932
[SPEAKER_01]: And he ended it by saying that he hoped to be able to carry through Michael's, excuse me, carry through Steve's work

648
00:58:07,679 --> 00:58:09,760
[SPEAKER_01]: and what he put into the design here.

649
00:58:09,840 --> 00:58:12,142
[SPEAKER_01]: So, Steve will live on with us.

650
00:58:14,403 --> 00:58:24,790
[SPEAKER_04]: I was a little disappointed when I seen the death notice that they didn't put in the employee of the Metropolitan County.

651
00:58:25,451 --> 00:58:27,132
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, we were too, Michael.

652
00:58:27,532 --> 00:58:36,198
[SPEAKER_01]: And I think what happened, having been through this myself recently, is that the person who wrote that up said, well, tell us something about him.

653
00:58:37,198 --> 00:58:45,044
[SPEAKER_01]: and they said, well, he was direct and he was hardworking and he was a great father, but they never, it would have been his wife and someone else.

654
00:58:45,765 --> 00:58:53,891
[SPEAKER_01]: And, you know, when Barbara and I met with her the day after, as I said, and I've talked with her and Michael and I are going to meet with her next week.

655
00:58:55,833 --> 00:59:02,678
[SPEAKER_01]: Legitimately, she was very upset and I would have hoped that the funeral home would have pulled that information out.

656
00:59:03,319 --> 00:59:05,000
[SPEAKER_01]: We're going to be represented

657
00:59:06,274 --> 00:59:12,376
[SPEAKER_01]: At the funeral, a good number of the staff has indicated that they're going to go to the wake.

658
00:59:13,196 --> 00:59:19,798
[SPEAKER_01]: And I'm going to allow anyone at the authority who wants to go to go on Monday to the funeral.

659
00:59:20,459 --> 00:59:23,120
[SPEAKER_01]: And we'll have someone working in the reception area.

660
00:59:23,160 --> 00:59:27,841
[SPEAKER_01]: But short of that, if the rest of the staff wants to go to that, they certainly can and I've encouraged them to do so.

661
00:59:28,561 --> 00:59:30,422
[SPEAKER_01]: The maintenance personnel are going to

662
00:59:31,327 --> 00:59:37,848
[SPEAKER_01]: wash all the red trucks and they're gonna put that in the funeral procession, each one of them.

663
00:59:39,509 --> 00:59:44,149
[SPEAKER_01]: Steve was an excellent worker and he was a good friend.

664
00:59:46,550 --> 00:59:54,752
[SPEAKER_01]: And Michael, I remember you when I was appointed as the ED back in May, May 10th of 2017, I remember it.

665
00:59:58,020 --> 01:00:05,544
[SPEAKER_01]: You were talking so highly of Steve Dattaro during that interview process, and Steve was in the audience afterwards.

666
01:00:05,584 --> 01:00:06,945
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know if you remember what I did.

667
01:00:07,926 --> 01:00:11,448
[SPEAKER_01]: I didn't go up and I thanked the board collectively.

668
01:00:11,468 --> 01:00:18,032
[SPEAKER_01]: I only shook everyone's hand after I'd gone over to Steve, and I shook Steve's hand and I said, you and I are going to be best friends.

669
01:00:18,932 --> 01:00:19,392
[SPEAKER_01]: And we were.

670
01:00:20,493 --> 01:00:20,793
[SPEAKER_01]: We were.

671
01:00:20,813 --> 01:00:25,656
[SPEAKER_04]: Is that you?

672
01:00:27,842 --> 01:00:32,588
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, there it is.

673
01:00:34,349 --> 01:00:35,671
[SPEAKER_04]: I think I mentioned it last time.

674
01:00:35,711 --> 01:00:38,534
[SPEAKER_04]: Can you send me a bouquet of flowers?

675
01:00:39,155 --> 01:00:39,695
[SPEAKER_07]: Yes.

676
01:00:39,836 --> 01:00:43,079
[SPEAKER_07]: I have a very large collection of money.

677
01:00:45,364 --> 01:00:57,667
[SPEAKER_07]: It's up to anybody if they would like to do that, but there is, we'll get flowers, edible oranges, and then whatever's left over, we'll... If anything's left over, will we give that to his wife?

678
01:00:57,687 --> 01:00:58,147
[SPEAKER_07]: We will.

679
01:00:58,787 --> 01:01:01,968
[SPEAKER_07]: We'll come up with a plan of something to do to help her going forward.

680
01:01:03,308 --> 01:01:03,708
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

681
01:01:04,549 --> 01:01:04,929
[SPEAKER_07]: Thank you.

682
01:01:05,969 --> 01:01:10,470
[SPEAKER_01]: I can't tell you how valuable Steve was, seriously.

683
01:01:23,906 --> 01:01:37,874
[SPEAKER_01]: I did reach out to all of you and to probably at least another 12 folks that were in my cell phone that I knew that Steve was close to.

684
01:01:38,754 --> 01:01:43,057
[SPEAKER_01]: We've had, I can't tell you how many times I've been stopped by the residents.

685
01:01:44,057 --> 01:01:46,799
[SPEAKER_01]: Yesterday, I went down to LaPrea before I left.

686
01:01:47,320 --> 01:01:53,225
[SPEAKER_01]: I had a resident call me over as I was exiting, and I came up to the car and expressed the concern.

687
01:01:53,245 --> 01:01:59,530
[SPEAKER_01]: I came back 20 minutes later, and I pulled into my spot, and I couldn't walk across because someone had blocked the roadway.

688
01:01:59,550 --> 01:02:03,113
[SPEAKER_01]: It was another resident telling me what they thought of Steve.

689
01:02:04,575 --> 01:02:08,098
[SPEAKER_01]: And Barbara was kind enough to post this at all the sites.

690
01:02:08,178 --> 01:02:13,082
[SPEAKER_01]: I've gotten emails from the residents relative to their

691
01:02:14,102 --> 01:02:17,784
[SPEAKER_01]: their concern and how much it was that they liked Steve.

692
01:02:19,565 --> 01:02:21,506
[SPEAKER_04]: I got two or three calls to him over the weekend.

693
01:02:21,926 --> 01:02:22,726
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I'm sure.

694
01:02:22,746 --> 01:02:26,568
[SPEAKER_01]: I think some of the calls you got, Michael, might have been the same people that were calling me.

695
01:02:29,649 --> 01:02:36,272
[SPEAKER_03]: I know the mayor called me and told me that Tuesday night at the city council meeting, this Tuesday coming up, they're going to do a moment of silence thing.

696
01:02:36,652 --> 01:02:36,852
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

697
01:02:36,892 --> 01:02:40,754
[SPEAKER_01]: One of the residents told me that they had spoken to the mayor and the mayor had indicated that.

698
01:02:40,794 --> 01:02:41,735
[SPEAKER_01]: I was happy to hear that.

699
01:02:42,275 --> 01:02:42,455
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

700
01:02:44,092 --> 01:02:48,994
[SPEAKER_01]: If you bear with me well you can continue on I'm gonna I'm looking for that that email that came in.

701
01:02:53,735 --> 01:02:57,637
[SPEAKER_07]: So do you need to go through each resolution?

702
01:02:57,957 --> 01:03:04,979
[SPEAKER_07]: Individually for the state budgets you need the first three items A, B, and C need a separate vote.

703
01:03:05,059 --> 01:03:06,800
[SPEAKER_07]: Federal votes can be voted on

704
01:03:08,794 --> 01:03:25,119
[SPEAKER_00]: Barbara, do you want Losa to read them out or do we just kind of make a motion to approve?

705
01:03:25,139 --> 01:03:27,540
[SPEAKER_07]: Just for the state ones you should read out separately.

706
01:03:27,560 --> 01:03:28,581
[SPEAKER_07]: Okay.

707
01:03:28,961 --> 01:03:33,242
[SPEAKER_01]: And the others it would be a resolution from the first number to the last number.

708
01:03:33,362 --> 01:03:36,063
[SPEAKER_09]: All right.

709
01:03:39,825 --> 01:03:41,026
[SPEAKER_09]: Resolution, yeah.

710
01:03:41,806 --> 01:03:45,407
[SPEAKER_08]: Would you like me to do it?

711
01:03:45,587 --> 01:03:46,607
[SPEAKER_08]: If you don't mind.

712
01:03:46,727 --> 01:04:05,411
[SPEAKER_08]: Resolution number 2021-044, consideration of requests of the executive director to approve the Medford Housing Authority original Wackling Court 400-1 state budget for the fiscal year 10-122 to September 30th, 23, as submitted with this agenda and subsequent submission to the Department of Housing and Community Development for review and approval.

713
01:04:05,431 --> 01:04:06,712
[SPEAKER_04]: I move approval.

714
01:04:07,172 --> 01:04:07,412
[SPEAKER_04]: Second.

715
01:04:09,001 --> 01:04:09,481
[SPEAKER_08]: All in favor?

716
01:04:09,802 --> 01:04:12,083
[SPEAKER_04]: Aye.

717
01:04:12,123 --> 01:04:30,654
[SPEAKER_08]: Resolution number 2021-045 consideration of requests of the executive director to approve the Medford Housing Authority original chapter 689 state budget for the fiscal year 10-1-22 to 9-30-23 as submitted with this agenda and subsequent submission to the Department of Housing and Community Development for review and approval.

718
01:04:32,835 --> 01:04:33,395
[SPEAKER_04]: Move to approval.

719
01:04:33,756 --> 01:04:34,096
[SPEAKER_04]: Second.

720
01:04:34,803 --> 01:04:35,283
[SPEAKER_08]: All in favor?

