778
01:08:50,608 --> 01:08:51,068
[SPEAKER_09]: Oh, yes.

779
01:08:51,128 --> 01:08:52,169
[SPEAKER_09]: Personal policy.

780
01:08:58,867 --> 01:09:12,354
[SPEAKER_01]: In my 30 plus years of working in public housing and representing public housing authorities, I've had two instances where a housing authority has had to deal with a deceased employee.

781
01:09:13,395 --> 01:09:14,175
[SPEAKER_01]: And this is one of them.

782
01:09:15,396 --> 01:09:24,161
[SPEAKER_01]: Michael and I were looking at what the benefits would be for a deceased employee.

783
01:09:24,721 --> 01:09:26,982
[SPEAKER_01]: And we looked at the personnel policy and

784
01:09:29,445 --> 01:09:36,708
[SPEAKER_01]: The sick time buyback is, the way it's written presently, is limited to individuals who retire.

785
01:09:37,669 --> 01:09:44,472
[SPEAKER_01]: The whole purpose of that is that if someone were to go to other employment, they couldn't take a sick leave buyback.

786
01:09:45,152 --> 01:10:06,138
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm recommending that we amend that policy so that it includes deceased individuals will get 20% of their sick time buyback, or their estate will, their heir, and that we incorporate that into the personnel policy beginning effective October 1 of this year.

787
01:10:08,623 --> 01:10:09,483
[SPEAKER_08]: I have no problem with that.

788
01:10:09,563 --> 01:10:13,947
[SPEAKER_08]: Is that, do other agencies with that in their personnel policy?

789
01:10:14,387 --> 01:10:15,508
[SPEAKER_01]: That I haven't investigated.

790
01:10:17,235 --> 01:10:18,496
[SPEAKER_01]: I didn't take the time to do that.

791
01:10:18,516 --> 01:10:19,456
[SPEAKER_01]: I didn't have the time to do that.

792
01:10:19,476 --> 01:10:22,838
[SPEAKER_08]: I just didn't know if you anecdotally had, that's why it came to you because you had seen it.

793
01:10:22,858 --> 01:10:30,281
[SPEAKER_01]: It came to me, honestly it came to me because of this instance and Michael had gone over the figures and I saw what the figures were.

794
01:10:30,301 --> 01:10:44,087
[SPEAKER_01]: I read the area in the personnel policy to make sure there was a citation in there as far as the general laws were concerned which dealt more with retirement in itself as opposed to

795
01:10:46,188 --> 01:10:52,191
[SPEAKER_01]: Excuse me, it dealt more with sick leave than it did with retirement or an individual being deceased.

796
01:10:53,051 --> 01:10:58,894
[SPEAKER_01]: You know, it was a benefit that Steve was actually looking to retire in a relatively short period of time.

797
01:10:58,914 --> 01:11:03,015
[SPEAKER_01]: He would have taken that and it would have been a significant amount.

798
01:11:04,116 --> 01:11:09,058
[SPEAKER_01]: And like I said, this has happened only twice in 30 plus years that I've been involved.

799
01:11:09,858 --> 01:11:13,340
[SPEAKER_01]: And I was involved with a number of housing authorities before I came here.

800
01:11:14,275 --> 01:11:18,238
[SPEAKER_01]: So it's not necessarily something that is a routine occurrence.

801
01:11:19,518 --> 01:11:28,684
[SPEAKER_01]: And I would be coming to the board with that had Steve not passed away because I would have thought it would have been something that we needed to include.

802
01:11:29,485 --> 01:11:36,009
[SPEAKER_01]: And from what I'm aware, and maybe this is an answer, Kaylene, that might help.

803
01:11:36,650 --> 01:11:42,774
[SPEAKER_01]: But as far as I'm aware, there's not anything that would prohibit the housing authority from doing that.

804
01:11:44,066 --> 01:11:51,189
[SPEAKER_01]: And DHCD looks at it, as far as DHCD is concerned, they look at the buyback being at no more than 20%.

805
01:11:51,349 --> 01:11:53,610
[SPEAKER_08]: I was going to say, where did the 20 come from?

806
01:11:54,430 --> 01:11:54,610
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

807
01:11:55,791 --> 01:11:57,592
[SPEAKER_01]: That's my understanding of where that's coming from.

808
01:11:57,612 --> 01:12:01,533
[SPEAKER_01]: Michael, you may know that better than I, but that's my understanding, is that 20%.

809
01:12:02,354 --> 01:12:09,717
[SPEAKER_01]: And that personnel policy was developed in conjunction with Michelle Randazzo and Masnaro.

810
01:12:10,697 --> 01:12:13,118
[SPEAKER_01]: So I would anticipate that that is correct.

811
01:12:16,250 --> 01:12:18,071
[SPEAKER_08]: So you'd like a motion- Sounds good to me.

812
01:12:18,091 --> 01:12:20,391
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, I'm all for it.

813
01:12:20,411 --> 01:12:26,613
[SPEAKER_01]: To instruct me to amend the personnel policy to include in sick time buyback that deceased employees.

814
01:12:27,554 --> 01:12:37,897
[SPEAKER_08]: The 20% of their sick buyback would go to family or- Yes, it would just be where it would say retiree would also include deceased.

815
01:12:38,954 --> 01:12:40,295
[SPEAKER_08]: So retiree right now only gets 20%?

816
01:12:40,475 --> 01:12:41,195
[SPEAKER_08]: Yes.

817
01:12:41,575 --> 01:12:44,837
[SPEAKER_01]: Oh, I thought they got... They get 100% of vacation.

818
01:12:44,957 --> 01:12:45,157
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, right.

819
01:12:45,177 --> 01:12:45,797
[SPEAKER_01]: And that's by law.

820
01:12:45,917 --> 01:12:47,018
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

821
01:12:47,278 --> 01:12:50,959
[SPEAKER_08]: And his... Okay, so it's amended to include also and death of employee.

822
01:12:51,620 --> 01:12:53,060
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, yes, yep.

823
01:12:54,121 --> 01:12:55,161
[SPEAKER_01]: Michael, that's correct, right?

824
01:12:55,181 --> 01:12:56,002
[SPEAKER_01]: That's correct, yes.

825
01:12:56,182 --> 01:12:56,562
[SPEAKER_01]: Okay.

826
01:12:57,142 --> 01:12:58,683
[SPEAKER_09]: So can I get a second on that?

827
01:12:58,923 --> 01:12:59,643
[SPEAKER_09]: I'll second it.

828
