[SPEAKER_09]: It's all yours, Jess.

851
01:13:41,119 --> 01:13:41,699
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

852
01:13:41,719 --> 01:13:43,520
[SPEAKER_01]: Barbara, can you pull that back up?

853
01:13:43,900 --> 01:13:43,960
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes.

854
01:13:46,784 --> 01:13:53,488
[SPEAKER_01]: Since Commissioner Holien is concerned that I may be delaying meetings, I'll have a brief executive director's report.

855
01:13:54,288 --> 01:13:55,409
[SPEAKER_01]: This is from Ben Wilson.

856
01:13:56,890 --> 01:14:02,073
[SPEAKER_01]: Gabe and MAJ team, I am so sorry for your loss of a special colleague and friend.

857
01:14:02,593 --> 01:14:04,694
[SPEAKER_01]: I am sure he will be missed tremendously.

858
01:14:04,714 --> 01:14:10,057
[SPEAKER_01]: I will always remember his noble, straightforward, cut to the chase approach.

859
01:14:10,798 --> 01:14:14,780
[SPEAKER_01]: A force that helped to get the salt install renovation project to this point.

860
01:14:15,347 --> 01:14:21,531
[SPEAKER_01]: I will be trying to hold on to some of Steve's clarity as we go through the upcoming challenges.

861
01:14:21,991 --> 01:14:26,374
[SPEAKER_01]: I was lucky to have worked with Steve for a very short but impressionable time.

862
01:14:26,554 --> 01:14:27,034
[SPEAKER_01]: We'll miss him.

863
01:14:30,416 --> 01:14:31,597
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, that is nice.

864
01:14:32,117 --> 01:14:33,018
[SPEAKER_01]: Get it right on the head too.

865
01:14:34,213 --> 01:14:35,034
[SPEAKER_01]: here right on the head.

866
01:14:35,254 --> 01:14:36,034
[SPEAKER_07]: First impressions.

867
01:14:36,395 --> 01:14:36,775
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

868
01:14:37,355 --> 01:14:40,498
[SPEAKER_01]: When we were first, I've said this a couple of times, but I'll say it again.

869
01:14:40,898 --> 01:15:02,814
[SPEAKER_01]: When we were first looking to how to design this building and coming up with ideas, and I'm not a construction person to the point that I would know the difference between a four-pipe system and a two-pipe system, but Steve was one of the utilities on the roof, and with that, it was gonna be a four-pipe system, and that's what he advocated for.

870
01:15:04,282 --> 01:15:10,443
[SPEAKER_01]: When the design came out, based upon a cost concern, it was a two pipe system.

871
01:15:12,364 --> 01:15:13,784
[SPEAKER_01]: To say the least, Steve was not happy.

872
01:15:13,804 --> 01:15:18,525
[SPEAKER_01]: To say the least, he made everyone aware he was not happy.

873
01:15:19,506 --> 01:15:22,486
[SPEAKER_01]: Unfortunately, and Paul, you know more about these things than I do.

874
01:15:23,306 --> 01:15:29,728
[SPEAKER_01]: But unfortunately, we're at a two pipe system and we weren't able to do a four pipe system, which Steve thought was the best way to do it.

875
01:15:30,492 --> 01:15:42,357
[SPEAKER_01]: If you don't do things the best way to do it, Steve's going to let you know, even though, according to the engineers, the two-pipe system, in addition to some of the other things that were going to do with that, was more than adequate.

876
01:15:42,777 --> 01:15:48,019
[SPEAKER_01]: But it was to the point where NC participated in every one of the design meetings.

877
01:15:48,579 --> 01:15:54,962
[SPEAKER_01]: So I think that's one of the things that the architect is indicating.

878
01:15:55,740 --> 01:16:12,328
[SPEAKER_01]: As far as my report is concerned, I know that the question came up, Mr. Helene, as far as, I believe it was you, Paul, as far as the write-offs and how Michael indicated that there would be some credit reporting there.

879
01:16:13,028 --> 01:16:16,830
[SPEAKER_01]: We're looking through the MTW program to do credit reporting on the residents, but

880
01:16:17,857 --> 01:16:28,406
[SPEAKER_01]: Not for those residents who have left us because we do that when they owe us, but for those residents who are here because the MTW is trying to build a credit rating for folks so they can move on.

881
01:16:29,407 --> 01:16:36,153
[SPEAKER_01]: And so we're going to be reporting to credit bureaus the success of those residents who are in that MTW program.

882
01:16:36,633 --> 01:16:38,575
[SPEAKER_01]: And we have a meeting coming up next week, Jennifer.

883
01:16:39,258 --> 01:16:48,244
[SPEAKER_01]: and Director of Management, and Sandy, the Resident Services Supervisor, with an entity who actually works with other housing authorities to create asset building programs.

884
01:16:48,524 --> 01:16:50,625
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'll keep you appraised of that.

885
01:16:51,526 --> 01:16:59,331
[SPEAKER_01]: Dietz, our architect at Walkman Court, we've met with them and continue to meet with them on multiple occasions, weekly at this point.

886
01:16:59,451 --> 01:17:01,432
[SPEAKER_01]: It'll eventually become once a week.

887
01:17:02,758 --> 01:17:08,265
[SPEAKER_01]: but we had a neighborhood meeting I believe that was after the last board meeting with the abutters.

888
01:17:08,325 --> 01:17:19,719
[SPEAKER_01]: We had two resident meetings and we have within the next two weeks a neighborhood meeting relative to not only the direct abutters but the entire neighborhood.

889
01:17:20,100 --> 01:17:21,421
[SPEAKER_01]: Gabe and I have met with the

890
01:17:22,102 --> 01:17:27,965
[SPEAKER_01]: The city in particular, the Community Preservation Committee chair and the representative from the Community Development Agency.

891
01:17:28,025 --> 01:17:31,647
[SPEAKER_01]: So I know Lohser, you and I spoke about that in particular with the CPC.

892
01:17:32,768 --> 01:17:39,892
[SPEAKER_01]: And I had sent some correspondence to the mayor requesting that there be a home rule petition.

893
01:17:40,663 --> 01:17:58,835
[SPEAKER_01]: which would be advantageous to the Housing Authority where, as far as construction related costs, that as other communities have done, we would waive the right for the sub-bid requirements, but not the right, I mentioned this I believe at the last meeting, not the wage rates.

894
01:17:59,595 --> 01:18:07,380
[SPEAKER_01]: And that would allow the Housing Authority more flexibility in being able to expand the field as far as eligible contractors are concerned.

895
01:18:08,462 --> 01:18:21,729
[SPEAKER_01]: And I will be meeting with the mayor and or her legal advisor on that and requesting that the mayor submit that home rule petition to the City Council for submission to the legislature.

896
01:18:21,969 --> 01:18:26,091
[SPEAKER_01]: And that's something that I'm hopeful will happen fairly, fairly quickly.

897
01:18:27,352 --> 01:18:31,674
[SPEAKER_01]: Michael, you had indicated that there's a number of open positions at the authority.

898
01:18:33,602 --> 01:18:37,545
[SPEAKER_01]: Two interviews today, both seem to be successful upon checking the references.

899
01:18:38,065 --> 01:18:41,328
[SPEAKER_01]: Two administrative positions, one in maintenance and one which would be a float.

900
01:18:42,249 --> 01:18:46,952
[SPEAKER_01]: And I have an interview tomorrow with the plumber, with a journeyman plumber.

901
01:18:47,633 --> 01:18:50,095
[SPEAKER_01]: And we'll see, that's a recommendation.

902
01:18:50,135 --> 01:18:56,299
[SPEAKER_01]: The way we do hiring here is that the immediate supervisor will review the resumes that come in to Barbara.

903
01:18:57,120 --> 01:18:59,762
[SPEAKER_01]: And then they'll make a decision whether or not to interview.

904
01:19:00,442 --> 01:19:02,424
[SPEAKER_01]: Usually we have two people who sit in on the interview.

905
01:19:03,154 --> 01:19:07,599
[SPEAKER_01]: They'll recommend folks to me, and then I will do the final interview.

906
01:19:08,040 --> 01:19:10,983
[SPEAKER_01]: It's a nice check and balance, if you may.

907
01:19:15,788 --> 01:19:19,893
[SPEAKER_01]: Lastly, we're going to see an uptake in legal activity.

908
01:19:20,774 --> 01:19:22,336
[SPEAKER_01]: Right now, I have 18 cases.

909
01:19:24,346 --> 01:19:29,349
[SPEAKER_01]: that we're working on for numerous lease violations.

910
01:19:29,869 --> 01:19:33,932
[SPEAKER_01]: And some of those will result in agreements, some of those will result in evictions.

911
01:19:35,353 --> 01:19:38,314
[SPEAKER_01]: I was in court this morning with an individual.

912
01:19:38,694 --> 01:19:42,136
[SPEAKER_01]: We had a trial and the judge ruled in our favor.

913
01:19:42,497 --> 01:19:48,180
[SPEAKER_01]: And that was a result of unauthorized occupants that were in the unit.

914
01:19:49,322 --> 01:19:55,725
[SPEAKER_01]: where there was a fire that cost the Housing Authority $287,000 that we're presently renovating.

915
01:19:56,825 --> 01:19:58,646
[SPEAKER_01]: So that we acted on that.

916
01:19:59,406 --> 01:20:04,148
[SPEAKER_01]: There's a number of residents who participated in the emergency

917
01:20:05,295 --> 01:20:09,437
[SPEAKER_01]: rent program through the pandemic called Shara that ended on April 15th.

918
01:20:09,678 --> 01:20:11,138
[SPEAKER_01]: We received payments for that.

919
01:20:11,178 --> 01:20:17,542
[SPEAKER_01]: I believe it was for probably 20 to maybe 30 residents sometime in May.

920
01:20:18,843 --> 01:20:23,325
[SPEAKER_01]: There's a six month grace period before we can begin any action against them.

921
01:20:23,345 --> 01:20:25,847
[SPEAKER_01]: A good number of those expire on November 20th.

922
01:20:26,748 --> 01:20:32,793
[SPEAKER_01]: and a good number of the individuals who receive that will be getting correspondence from me and will be visiting in court.

923
01:20:33,854 --> 01:20:35,696
[SPEAKER_01]: Michael indicated the write-offs, so he left.

924
01:20:36,076 --> 01:20:37,317
[SPEAKER_01]: Michael indicated the write-offs.

925
01:20:37,778 --> 01:20:50,629
[SPEAKER_01]: We're going to look to try to work with these folks, but a number of them are fairly extensive, and so that I would anticipate that the write-offs next year might be a little bit higher than this year, but hopefully that's proven wrong.

926
01:20:51,049 --> 01:20:52,811
[SPEAKER_01]: Hopefully it's proven wrong.

927
01:20:53,601 --> 01:20:56,163
[SPEAKER_01]: Madam Chair, that's the extent of my report.

928
01:20:56,223 --> 01:21:01,447
[SPEAKER_01]: If anyone has any questions, I'd be certainly willing to attempt to address them.

929
01:21:01,607 --> 01:21:02,748
[SPEAKER_04]: Madam Chair, if I may.

930
01:21:03,589 --> 01:21:07,071
[SPEAKER_04]: Yes, on October 9th at 6.15 p.m.

931
01:21:07,231 --> 01:21:10,194
[SPEAKER_04]: It was a Sunday.

932
01:21:11,995 --> 01:21:14,477
[SPEAKER_04]: My wife and myself were driving up Riverside Ave.

933
01:21:15,517 --> 01:21:17,399
[SPEAKER_04]: Three police cars in front of the building.

934
01:21:19,420 --> 01:21:21,142
[SPEAKER_04]: Were you aware of that?

935
01:21:22,785 --> 01:21:24,385
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm not aware of that time, Michael.

936
01:21:24,445 --> 01:21:32,187
[SPEAKER_01]: I am aware, though, that the police have been here for at least one instance, maybe more.

937
01:21:33,247 --> 01:21:34,828
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know what the date or the time was.

938
01:21:35,608 --> 01:21:40,329
[SPEAKER_04]: I'm talking about October 9th at 6.15 p.m.

939
01:21:40,349 --> 01:21:41,249
[SPEAKER_04]: Sunday night.

940
01:21:41,289 --> 01:21:41,769
[SPEAKER_04]: Right.

941
01:21:42,249 --> 01:21:44,990
[SPEAKER_01]: I had a meeting with the staff today, the management staff,

942
01:21:45,938 --> 01:21:52,344
[SPEAKER_01]: and they did alert me to an instance where the police were alerted for this building.

943
01:21:53,445 --> 01:22:06,037
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know that that was the time, but it dealt with a resident's son who may have assaulted someone or may have assaulted the mother.

944
01:22:06,757 --> 01:22:09,700
[SPEAKER_01]: I don't know that yet because we're in the process of getting the police report.

945
01:22:10,661 --> 01:22:11,622
[SPEAKER_01]: Usually they'll reach out

946
01:22:12,633 --> 01:22:19,317
[SPEAKER_01]: And they'll oftentimes reach out to either me or Chris April because they have a lot of interaction with Chris being on the family site.

947
01:22:19,357 --> 01:22:22,999
[SPEAKER_01]: So sometimes they'll be dealing with him on something and then they'll mention it.

948
01:22:23,979 --> 01:22:40,928
[SPEAKER_01]: But I'm at a point right now where in this instance, I am going to Somerville District Court more than likely, if not tomorrow, then on Monday.

949
01:22:41,476 --> 01:22:45,637
[SPEAKER_01]: to get filings there on two instances.

950
01:22:46,217 --> 01:22:53,019
[SPEAKER_01]: One here, I believe the other one was at Willis Ave.

951
01:22:53,579 --> 01:22:57,721
[SPEAKER_01]: And then I am also going on my way in within the next few days.

952
01:22:58,221 --> 01:23:05,483
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm going to stop at Quincy District Court because there was an incident with one of our residents who had

953
01:23:07,567 --> 01:23:15,012
[SPEAKER_01]: some sort of a violent act committed on them by someone who I believe may be living in a unit unauthorized.

954
01:23:15,532 --> 01:23:28,320
[SPEAKER_01]: So I'm going to pull that police report or that complaint in court to see if in fact that individual's address that is not supposed to be living in this unit is actually in that unit.

955
01:23:28,924 --> 01:23:36,447
[SPEAKER_01]: So it's just a number of the things that we do to try to get enough evidence to go after these folks.

956
01:23:36,707 --> 01:23:44,711
[SPEAKER_01]: And we were alerted to that by our own police, because the Quincy police were looking for information.

957
01:23:44,991 --> 01:23:48,112
[SPEAKER_04]: One other thing, and then I'll let it go.

958
01:23:48,912 --> 01:23:51,974
[SPEAKER_04]: Down at Tamponi, I know police go down there.

959
01:23:52,714 --> 01:23:55,175
[SPEAKER_04]: Sometimes they have a farm.

960
01:23:56,170 --> 01:23:58,511
[SPEAKER_04]: the police, that they can get into the building?

961
01:23:59,531 --> 01:23:59,831
[SPEAKER_04]: They do.

962
01:24:00,192 --> 01:24:06,974
[SPEAKER_04]: Some of them do, and some of them don't, and they usually park over by the garage.

963
01:24:08,094 --> 01:24:10,635
[SPEAKER_04]: So I'm just wondering why some do and some don't.

964
01:24:10,655 --> 01:24:14,877
[SPEAKER_01]: I mean... Yes, we don't want to hand out... They walk through the whole building.

965
01:24:14,897 --> 01:24:15,277
[SPEAKER_01]: Right.

966
01:24:15,317 --> 01:24:21,599
[SPEAKER_01]: We don't want to hand out fobs to everyone, to multiple fobs without being able to take control of them.

967
01:24:22,239 --> 01:24:23,960
[SPEAKER_01]: So we were requested that

968
01:24:25,763 --> 01:24:28,866
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm going to guess, Michael, maybe a year and a half, two years ago.

969
01:24:30,087 --> 01:24:33,550
[SPEAKER_01]: And that was provided to the detectives.

970
01:24:34,310 --> 01:24:40,636
[SPEAKER_01]: And the offices on patrol are supposed to reach out to the detective.

971
01:24:40,976 --> 01:24:43,018
[SPEAKER_01]: And I don't know where they keep it.

972
01:24:43,038 --> 01:24:44,859
[SPEAKER_01]: They may keep it at the front desk for all I know.

973
01:24:45,600 --> 01:24:47,461
[SPEAKER_01]: But that detective, I forget which one we gave it to.

974
01:24:47,501 --> 01:24:50,524
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm not sure if it was Detective Mattis or some of the others.

975
01:24:50,584 --> 01:24:52,786
[SPEAKER_01]: I know we deal with Detective Mattis quite frequently.

976
01:24:53,780 --> 01:24:55,221
[SPEAKER_01]: that they were going to be in control of that.

977
01:24:55,421 --> 01:24:58,803
[SPEAKER_01]: But prior to that, they didn't have access to the building.

978
01:24:59,063 --> 01:25:02,305
[SPEAKER_01]: So it's just a matter of control.

979
01:25:02,966 --> 01:25:11,091
[SPEAKER_01]: We have more control today than we've ever had because we limit the number of fobs that go out to one.

980
01:25:11,511 --> 01:25:14,693
[SPEAKER_01]: We don't give two because we never had control over that second one.

981
01:25:16,034 --> 01:25:21,717
[SPEAKER_01]: And when we find that someone is abusing that, we can see who it is.

982
01:25:22,613 --> 01:25:27,517
[SPEAKER_01]: and there's sometimes that we've had to shut it off when there's been unauthorized occupants who've been coming in.

983
01:25:28,538 --> 01:25:35,583
[SPEAKER_01]: Because we do have an issue with, every housing authority, Kayleen can tell you, we do have an issue with unauthorized occupants and it's tough to prove.

984
01:25:36,023 --> 01:25:37,704
[SPEAKER_08]: You've been in a little old Lexington.

985
01:25:38,085 --> 01:25:38,345
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah.

986
01:25:38,865 --> 01:25:40,026
[SPEAKER_01]: You don't have that in Lexington.

987
01:25:40,086 --> 01:25:41,167
[SPEAKER_06]: Of course we do.

988
01:25:41,227 --> 01:25:41,827
[SPEAKER_06]: No.

989
01:25:41,967 --> 01:25:41,827
100%.

990
01:25:42,047 --> 01:25:44,409
[SPEAKER_06]: Not in Lexington.

991
01:25:44,449 --> 01:25:44,790
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you.

992
01:25:44,850 --> 01:25:47,572
[SPEAKER_01]: They may have one to every 10 that we have, but they do have one.

993
01:25:47,592 --> 01:25:50,113
[SPEAKER_09]: Is that all?

994
01:25:50,133 --> 01:25:50,514
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

995
01:25:50,814 --> 01:25:51,574
[SPEAKER_01]: Thank you, Madam Chair.

996
01:25:51,635 --> 01:25:52,215
[SPEAKER_09]: You're welcome.

997
01:25:53,044 --> 01:25:54,184
[SPEAKER_09]: Is there anything else?

998
01:25:54,865 --> 01:25:58,366
[SPEAKER_09]: Can I get a motion to close the Executive Director report?

999
01:25:58,386 --> 01:26:01,127
[SPEAKER_04]: I'll make the motion to close the Executive Director report.

1000
01:26:01,307 --> 01:26:01,688
[SPEAKER_04]: Thank you.

1001
01:26:01,808 --> 01:26:02,268
[SPEAKER_04]: One second.

1002
01:26:02,568 --> 01:26:03,068
[SPEAKER_09]: Thank you.

1003
01:26:03,268 --> 01:26:03,908
[SPEAKER_09]: All in favor?

1004
01:26:04,509 --> 01:26:04,889
[SPEAKER_04]: Aye.

1005
01:26:06,490 --> 01:26:08,851
[SPEAKER_09]: Management report, is that included with that, Jeff?

1006
01:26:08,871 --> 01:26:09,911
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes, yes.

1007
01:26:09,931 --> 01:26:12,212
[SPEAKER_01]: I didn't reference it, but it's the report.

1008
01:26:12,232 --> 01:26:14,473
[SPEAKER_01]: If anyone has any questions on any of those things, let me know.

1009
01:26:14,533 --> 01:26:14,813
[SPEAKER_01]: All right.

1010
01:26:15,513 --> 01:26:16,133
[SPEAKER_09]: All business?

1011
01:26:16,934 --> 01:26:18,154
[SPEAKER_09]: Move to all business.

1012
01:26:18,414 --> 01:26:19,235
[SPEAKER_09]: Resolution number 2022-053.

1013
01:26:22,623 --> 01:26:38,911
[SPEAKER_09]: consideration of request by Executive Director to approve a contract to Belco Landscaping of Salem, New Hampshire for MHC job number 2202, M1, 10-pound apartment, site improvement, gazebo, and fence replacement.

1014
01:26:38,931 --> 01:26:40,812
[SPEAKER_09]: The total amount of the contract is $121,900.

1015
01:26:40,852 --> 01:26:45,154
[SPEAKER_09]: Madam Chair, if I may.

1016
01:26:46,615 --> 01:26:46,815
[SPEAKER_09]: Wait.

1017
01:26:47,336 --> 01:26:50,057
[SPEAKER_01]: If I may, this was the item that was tabled

1018
01:26:51,252 --> 01:26:59,536
[SPEAKER_01]: from last month, and I've had two meetings concerning this, one with Gabe and one with Gabe and the owner of the company.

1019
01:27:00,516 --> 01:27:20,304
[SPEAKER_01]: When I asked Gabe why it was that there was that instance, and this was recommended, he said that he routinely checks and Googles the companies, and that he didn't do it in this instance because a few months earlier,

1020
01:27:21,625 --> 01:27:25,867
[SPEAKER_01]: prior to the Department of Labor's finding and being reported, he had Googled them.

1021
01:27:27,108 --> 01:27:31,411
[SPEAKER_01]: And that they had done work for us and had done an exceptional job.

1022
01:27:32,571 --> 01:27:33,432
[SPEAKER_01]: That was on a Friday.

1023
01:27:33,452 --> 01:27:36,353
[SPEAKER_01]: I think it was on a Friday after our board meeting.

1024
01:27:37,154 --> 01:27:47,539
[SPEAKER_01]: Shortly thereafter, on Monday, Gabe and I had a meeting with the designer who was on the project and the owner of the company.

1025
01:27:48,200 --> 01:27:50,621
[SPEAKER_01]: And he explained that for a period of time,

1026
01:27:51,293 --> 01:27:57,276
[SPEAKER_01]: that they were paying their employees at request of the employees cash.

1027
01:27:58,737 --> 01:28:02,759
[SPEAKER_01]: And that they were aware that it was wrong to do so.

1028
01:28:03,520 --> 01:28:06,061
[SPEAKER_01]: He said that they've paid the penalty.

1029
01:28:06,181 --> 01:28:08,062
[SPEAKER_01]: Everyone has been paid what they should have been paid.

1030
01:28:08,563 --> 01:28:17,247
[SPEAKER_01]: And that the penalty was in excess of what it was that they actually paid the employees.

1031
01:28:19,019 --> 01:28:24,881
[SPEAKER_01]: The reason why Gabe had recommended them and still recommends them is the fact that two reasons.

1032
01:28:25,862 --> 01:28:33,945
[SPEAKER_01]: One is that they did work as far as they did the fence replacement at Walkland Court, which he said went exceptionally well.

1033
01:28:34,965 --> 01:28:37,926
[SPEAKER_01]: He felt that the company was very responsive.

1034
01:28:39,487 --> 01:28:47,050
[SPEAKER_01]: And secondly, the second low bidder was the contractor who did the

1035
01:28:48,921 --> 01:28:57,290
[SPEAKER_01]: The upgrade of the landscaping at Willis Avenue is approximately, I don't have the exact number, between $300,000 and $400,000.

1036
01:28:57,590 --> 01:29:05,299
[SPEAKER_01]: And it's the only time in five years that I've had to meet with a contractor because that was not as successful.

1037
01:29:05,339 --> 01:29:07,482
[SPEAKER_01]: Now it may have been the second low bidder sub.

1038
01:29:08,433 --> 01:29:10,794
[SPEAKER_01]: but there were issues that we had on that.

1039
01:29:10,914 --> 01:29:14,374
[SPEAKER_01]: So that was the reason why Gabe approved them.

1040
01:29:15,235 --> 01:29:25,717
[SPEAKER_01]: We also reached out to the Attorney General's office to ask them, what is the standard that we have to meet in order to reject a bid?

1041
01:29:26,537 --> 01:29:37,360
[SPEAKER_01]: And he indicated that in this instance, while it was up to the authorities, Board of Commissioners, to make that determination, it's not something that

1042
01:29:38,680 --> 01:29:43,904
[SPEAKER_01]: they felt that it was not within the authorities, the board's authority to do so.

1043
01:29:44,164 --> 01:29:47,227
[SPEAKER_01]: So that it's up to the board is basically what they say.

1044
01:29:48,528 --> 01:29:49,969
[SPEAKER_01]: So it's up to the board to decide.

1045
01:29:59,335 --> 01:30:00,976
[SPEAKER_01]: So that's where we're at at this point in time.

1046
01:30:01,417 --> 01:30:07,161
[SPEAKER_01]: Gabe was happy with their performance, but I can certainly understand the concerns that the board may have.

1047
01:30:11,611 --> 01:30:13,352
[SPEAKER_03]: It's not really the performance.

1048
01:30:13,412 --> 01:30:15,813
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm sure the performance of the people working there are great.

1049
01:30:15,833 --> 01:30:18,295
[SPEAKER_03]: It was just the, you know, the guy did something illegal.

1050
01:30:18,315 --> 01:30:19,395
[SPEAKER_03]: He knew he was doing something illegal.

1051
01:30:19,475 --> 01:30:20,856
[SPEAKER_03]: It's just not, I don't like it.

1052
01:30:22,257 --> 01:30:25,078
[SPEAKER_01]: Yeah, his response, his response to that when I asked him.

1053
01:30:25,746 --> 01:30:32,348
[SPEAKER_01]: And I said, what is your response to this when you got fined by the DOL?

1054
01:30:32,808 --> 01:30:38,189
[SPEAKER_01]: And he said, we did it because they requested it, even though we knew it wasn't something we should have been doing.

1055
01:30:38,669 --> 01:30:40,830
[SPEAKER_01]: And he said, we don't do that anymore and we won't do it.

1056
01:30:41,190 --> 01:30:45,811
[SPEAKER_01]: He said that he has, I'm not sure if it was 20, Paul, or 30 employees.

1057
01:30:46,731 --> 01:30:50,312
[SPEAKER_01]: And I said, how many employees do you have that oversee this area?

1058
01:30:50,412 --> 01:30:52,172
[SPEAKER_01]: And he said, one and a half.

1059
01:30:54,373 --> 01:30:55,013
[SPEAKER_01]: One and a half people.

1060
01:30:59,754 --> 01:31:02,944
[SPEAKER_09]: I have no objection to it.

1061
01:31:02,964 --> 01:31:04,529
[SPEAKER_04]: You want me to withdraw the approval?

1062
01:31:06,988 --> 01:31:08,469
[SPEAKER_05]: I'm deferring to Paul.

1063
01:31:08,489 --> 01:31:09,909
[SPEAKER_03]: You gotta do what you gotta do.

1064
01:31:10,069 --> 01:31:11,410
[SPEAKER_03]: We have to vote on it anyways.

1065
01:31:11,670 --> 01:31:12,410
[SPEAKER_03]: It's a money thing.

1066
01:31:13,170 --> 01:31:14,791
[SPEAKER_03]: So you guys vote whatever way you want to vote.

1067
01:31:14,811 --> 01:31:16,431
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not voting for it, but you guys do what you want.

1068
01:31:16,451 --> 01:31:16,972
[SPEAKER_03]: It doesn't matter.

1069
01:31:17,212 --> 01:31:19,132
[SPEAKER_03]: They're still gonna use them either way.

1070
01:31:19,432 --> 01:31:20,133
[SPEAKER_03]: Vote yay or nay.

1071
01:31:20,393 --> 01:31:20,953
[SPEAKER_03]: You have to use it.

1072
01:31:21,213 --> 01:31:22,934
[SPEAKER_03]: It's part of the procedure for the bid, right?

1073
01:31:23,154 --> 01:31:24,714
[SPEAKER_01]: No, no, no.

1074
01:31:24,794 --> 01:31:30,076
[SPEAKER_01]: What the AG's office told us, it's up to the board to decide whether or not this is significant enough not to approve.

1075
01:31:30,476 --> 01:31:33,017
[SPEAKER_01]: And what would happen is that I would anticipate

1076
01:31:33,640 --> 01:31:41,304
[SPEAKER_01]: unless the board thinks over a period of time that nothing else has happened, that this is a contractor that we wouldn't be using in the future.

1077
01:31:42,705 --> 01:31:45,106
[SPEAKER_01]: Would you say the second bidder was someone you used before?

1078
01:31:45,426 --> 01:31:45,606
[SPEAKER_01]: Yes.

1079
01:31:45,646 --> 01:31:51,209
[SPEAKER_08]: So the housing authority is in like a rock and a hard place because the second low bidder is not up to standard.

1080
01:31:51,389 --> 01:31:53,150
[SPEAKER_03]: It's somebody they don't like that they've used before.

1081
01:31:53,310 --> 01:31:55,051
[SPEAKER_08]: And I also gave a bad recommendation.

1082
01:31:55,812 --> 01:31:56,172
[SPEAKER_08]: I've used them.

1083
01:31:56,539 --> 01:31:57,039
[SPEAKER_01]: for the second.

1084
01:31:57,920 --> 01:32:01,221
[SPEAKER_01]: I'm aware with the second one there was a problem with the sub.

1085
01:32:01,761 --> 01:32:06,723
[SPEAKER_01]: And I don't know if it was the performance of the sub or the oversight of the sub, but ultimately that was the responsibility of the GC.

1086
01:32:07,763 --> 01:32:10,184
[SPEAKER_01]: And it was with, like I said, it was with the GC that I spoke.

1087
01:32:10,224 --> 01:32:13,005
[SPEAKER_01]: And Kayleen, I wasn't aware that you had given a reference on that.

1088
01:32:14,105 --> 01:32:18,047
[SPEAKER_03]: I feel like, just to be clear, everybody should vote the way they feel.

1089
01:32:18,087 --> 01:32:18,627
[SPEAKER_03]: If they think that

1090
01:32:19,037 --> 01:32:21,739
[SPEAKER_03]: These people have done the right thing and they paid their penalty.

1091
01:32:21,779 --> 01:32:22,499
[SPEAKER_03]: You should vote that way.

1092
01:32:22,539 --> 01:32:23,240
[SPEAKER_03]: Don't vote with me.

1093
01:32:23,660 --> 01:32:25,742
[SPEAKER_03]: You vote what you think is going to be best for the housing authority.

1094
01:32:26,342 --> 01:32:30,084
[SPEAKER_03]: I personally don't like it because this guy went out, he broke a rule.

1095
01:32:30,565 --> 01:32:31,385
[SPEAKER_03]: He knew what he was doing.

1096
01:32:32,066 --> 01:32:36,689
[SPEAKER_03]: If his employees ask to get paid under the table, he's paying them under the table.

